<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="95" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">This new species is named after our colleague and friend L. Brian Patrick (Dakota Wesleyan University, USA), in recognition of his efforts in popularizing taxonomy via his podcast &quot;New Species&quot;.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="95" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">
The new species differs from the generotype, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="L.Koch" baseAuthorityYear="1866" class="Arachnida" family="Liocranidae" genus="Mesiotelus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesiotelus tenuissimus" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenuissimus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Mesiotelus tenuissimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L. Koch, 1866), by having a relatively longer, thinner and gradually tapering RTA which is about 3 times longer than its basal width (vs RTA with subparallel margins and less than 2 times longer than wide), a much longer median apophysis, about 
<normalizedToken originalValue="½">1/2</normalizedToken>
of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="tegulum’s">tegulum's</normalizedToken>
length (vs about 4 times shorter than tegulum), and a longer embolus terminating anteriorly from the tegulum (vs embolus short, spine-like and terminating beyond the anterior edge of the tegulum). The two species also differ by the course of sperm duct and the shape of the anterior tegular apophysis (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Aa</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="95" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">
Male (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">holotype</emphasis>
).
</emphasis>
Habitus as in Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Males of Zagrotes borna sp. nov. (A), Z. parla sp. nov. (B), Micaria atropatene sp. nov. (C), Sestakovaia hyrcania sp. nov. (D) and Mesiotelus patricki sp. nov. (E, F) A-D, F habitus, dorsal E chelicerae, ventral. Scale bars: 0.2 mm, unless stated otherwise." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1054.70408.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/573552" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">4F</figureCitation>
. Total length 5.22. Carapace 2.00 long, 1.85 wide. Eye sizes: AME: 0.12, ALE: 0.13, PME: 0.10, PLE: 0.10. Carapace, labium, chelicera, maxilla and sternum light brown. Chelicera with 2 pro- and 3 retromarginal teeth (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Males of Zagrotes borna sp. nov. (A), Z. parla sp. nov. (B), Micaria atropatene sp. nov. (C), Sestakovaia hyrcania sp. nov. (D) and Mesiotelus patricki sp. nov. (E, F) A-D, F habitus, dorsal E chelicerae, ventral. Scale bars: 0.2 mm, unless stated otherwise." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1054.70408.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/573552" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">4E</figureCitation>
). Legs yellowish-brown, without annulations. Abdomen dark grey, dorsally with indistinct chevron markings, ventrally lighter with distinct tracheal marks. Spinnerets light grey, unicolourous. Measurements of palp and legs: palp: 4.77 (1.74, 1.08, 1.08, 0.87), legs: I: 10.86 (2.77, 1.39, 2.95, 2.45, 1.30), II: 7.67 + missing tarsus (2.31, 1.08, 2.30, 1.98, missing), III: 7.38 (1.94, 0.91, 1.67, 1.95, 0.91), IV: 10.38 (2.63, 1.10, 2.48, 3.06, 1.11).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">
Palp as in Figures 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Male palp of Mesiotelus patricki sp. nov. A-D ventral, retrolateral, prolateral and dorsal, respectively E whole palp, prolateral. Scale bars: 0.2 mm, unless stated otherwise." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1054.70408.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/573559" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">11A-E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. SEM images of the male palp of Mesiotelus patricki sp. nov. A, B ventral C retroventral. Abbreviations: Aa - anterior apophysis, Co - conductor, Cs - curved setae, Em - embolus, Ta - tegular apophysis. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1054.70408.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/573560" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">12A-C</figureCitation>
; palp very long, almost as long as body, patella as long as tibia; tibia with 3 times longer than wide and gradually tapering RTA; cymbium twice shorter than femur, and 2 times longer than wide, tip as long as RTA, prolateral side with few very long and curled setae (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Cs</emphasis>
, Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. SEM images of the male palp of Mesiotelus patricki sp. nov. A, B ventral C retroventral. Abbreviations: Aa - anterior apophysis, Co - conductor, Cs - curved setae, Em - embolus, Ta - tegular apophysis. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1054.70408.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/573560" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">12A, B</figureCitation>
); bulb oval, 1.67 times longer than wide; sperm duct almost reaching posterior margin of tegulum; median apophysis long, almost as long as 
<normalizedToken originalValue="½">1/2</normalizedToken>
of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="tegulum’s">tegulum's</normalizedToken>
length; anterior tegular apophysis (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Aa</emphasis>
) bifid; embolus (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Em</emphasis>
) originates at about ca 6:30 
<normalizedToken originalValue="o’clock">o'clock</normalizedToken>
position, free part long, bent in terminal part and directed anteriorly.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/zookeys.1054.70408.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/573560" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" start="Figure 12" startId="F12">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">
